TY  - JOUR
T1  - Leader Characteristics, Self-Confidence, and Methods of Upward Influence in Organizational Decision Situations
AU  - Mowday, Richard T.
Y1  - 1979/12/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255810
DO  - 10.5465/255810
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 709
EP  - 725
VL  - 22
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study on the exercise of influence examines selected relationships among leader characteristics, self-confidence in exercising influence, and the likelihood of using several methods of influence in three organizational decision situations. Leader characteristics were found to be related to self-confidence in exercising influence, and self-confidence in exercising influence was found to be weakly related to the likelihood of using persuasive arguments as a method of influence.
AB  - This study on the exercise of influence examines selected relationships among leader characteristics, self-confidence in exercising influence, and the likelihood of using several methods of influence in three organizational decision situations. Leader characteristics were found to be related to self-confidence in exercising influence, and self-confidence in exercising influence was found to be weakly related to the likelihood of using persuasive arguments as a method of influence.
